      <hedline>
        <hl1>Support From the City</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Joseph Papp Public Theater producer George C Wolfe letter on Wendy Wasserstein's July 7 article says decision to present only Twelfth Night rather than two plays this summer was result of Public Theater's belt tightening, not New York City budget cuts</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Where Puck Casts a Spell Over Summer'' by Wendy Wasserstein [July 7]:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Where Puck Casts a Spell Over Summer'' by Wendy Wasserstein [July 7]:</p>
        <p>This summer the Joseph Papp Public Theater is presenting one Shakespeare in Central Park production: ''Twelfth Night,'' which will run for seven weeks, roughly double the normal schedule for one show, allowing us to offer nearly the same number of free tickets to the public.</p>
        <p>The decision to produce a single show this summer was the result of the Public Theater's having to tighten its belt in these difficult financial times. The decision was not the result of New York City budget cuts, as was suggested in Ms. Wasserstein's article. Mayor Michael R. Bloomberg and the rest of the city administration have been nothing but extremely supportive of the Public Theater.</p>
        <p>GEORGE C. WOLFE  Manhattan</p>
        <p>The writer is producer of the Joseph Papp Public Theater and the New York Shakespeare Festival.</p>
        <p>SHAKESPEARE</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
